This paper discusses decision-theoretic planning with non-Markovian rewards, which is a topic that falls under the intersection of several subfields in computer science. Based on the content of the abstract, the most likely sub-category is cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), as decision-theoretic planning is a core topic in AI research. The paper also mentions dynamic programming, heuristic search, and structured methods, which are common techniques in the fields of machine learning and robotics, suggesting that cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.RO (Robotics) are also likely sub-categories. The paper's focus on temporal logic and planning algorithms suggests that it may also be relevant to cs.PL (Programming Languages) and cs.SE (Software Engineering).
